summary:
“Gaiman: Well in terms of gender diversity, angels and demons, as stated 
in the book, have no gender... Archangel Uriel and...
body:
“Gaiman: Well in terms of gender diversity, angels and demons, as stated in the book, have no gender… Archangel Uriel and Archangel Michael are both played by women, Sandalfon and Gabriel are both played by men. “ (x)

Mr. Gaiman out here really doubling down on the fact that a big portion of the characters are canonically agender/genderqueer and can (and will) be played by anyone is really making my day here!

summary: They were in the cafeteria of the British Museum, another refuge for all weary foot soldiers of the Cold War. At the table to...
body:
They were in the cafeteria of the British Museum, another refuge for all weary foot soldiers of the Cold War. At the table to their left two ramrod-straight Americans in suits were surreptitiously handing over a briefcase full of deniable dollars to a small dark woman in sunglasses; at the table on their right the deputy head of M17 and the local KGB section officer argued over who got to keep the receipt for the tea and buns.

- Good Omens by Terry Pratchet & Neil Gaiman

title: Cutting Down on Expenses
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2TW7J2K

by questionablyevil

And then, of course, it had seemed even natural that they should, as it were, hold the fort for one
another whenever common sense dictated. Both were of angel stock, after all. If one was going to Hull
for a quick temptation, it made sense to nip across the city and carry out a standard brief moment of
divine ecstasy. It’d get done anyway, and being sensible about it gave everyone more free time and cut
down on expenses.
